<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF84B258FBCEFED6FB1AFEDF" box="[1057,1211,323,347]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">SCATOPSIDAE</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CEF66D9FFF84B25BFCD5FEF9FD0DFEB0" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="725" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" type="description">
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FEF9FC19FE04" blockId="13.[826,952,364,385]" box="[826,952,364,385]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FEF9FC19FE04" box="[826,952,364,385]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FE0EFAF8FE35" blockId="13.[826,1369,410,432]" box="[826,1369,410,432]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FE0EFC20FE35" box="[826,897,411,432]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Testis:</emphasis>
Each testis is oval-shaped (
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FB26FE0FFAECFE35" author="Loew H" box="[1225,1357,410,432]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" refId="ref22358" refString="Loew H. 1841. Horae Anatomicae, Beitrage zur Genaueren Antomischen Kenntniss der Evertebraten. Abteilung I. Entomotomien. Heine: Posen." type="book" year="1841">Loew, 1841</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FE5DFB09FE5B" blockId="13.[826,1192,456,478]" box="[826,1192,456,478]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FE5DFC64FE58" box="[826,965,456,477]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Epididymis:</emphasis>
Not differentiated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FE62FC5EFDED" blockId="13.[826,1442,502,616]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FE62FC6EFD8E" box="[826,975,502,524]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Vas deferens:</emphasis>
The ducts could not be traced in this study, but according to 
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FBBFFD80FB7EFDAE" author="Loew H" box="[1104,1247,533,555]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" refId="ref22358" refString="Loew H. 1841. Horae Anatomicae, Beitrage zur Genaueren Antomischen Kenntniss der Evertebraten. Abteilung I. Entomotomien. Heine: Posen." type="book" year="1841">Loew (1841)</bibRefCitation>
a pair of rather long and convoluted ducts enters separately a small expanded region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FD15FC4DFCAA" blockId="13.[826,1442,640,1122]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FD15FAA1FD10" box="[826,1280,640,661]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Accessory gland and seminal vesicle:</emphasis>
A small oval expansion is present at the apex of the ejaculatory duct (
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FC91FD28FBA0FD56" author="Loew H" box="[894,1025,701,723]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" refId="ref22358" refString="Loew H. 1841. Horae Anatomicae, Beitrage zur Genaueren Antomischen Kenntniss der Evertebraten. Abteilung I. Entomotomien. Heine: Posen." type="book" year="1841">Loew, 1841</bibRefCitation>
) and may correspond to a seminal vesicle. The paired vasa deferentia enter this vesicle separately. This structure could not be confirmed in our dissections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCBCFCADFCDFFBE7" blockId="13.[826,1442,640,1122]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">A pair of long tubular glands, with posteriorly recurved tips, dominates the posterior region of the genital tract. These thick-walled accessory glands lie dorsal to the sperm pump and rectum, arch anteroventrally and taper to narrow ducts that enter the sperm pump ventrally. The recurved tip appears to taper to a short nipple-shaped appendix. These glands are rather stout and the narrow extension of the gland to the sperm pump is also thick walled, with a narrow inner canal.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FBEFFC73FA8F" blockId="13.[826,1442,1146,1290]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FBEFFC5EFB0A" box="[826,1023,1146,1167]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Ejaculatory duct:</emphasis>
This duct could not be traced in the present study, but according to 
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FB74FB0CFA84FB2A" author="Loew H" box="[1179,1317,1177,1199]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" refId="ref22358" refString="Loew H. 1841. Horae Anatomicae, Beitrage zur Genaueren Antomischen Kenntniss der Evertebraten. Abteilung I. Entomotomien. Heine: Posen." type="book" year="1841">Loew (1841)</bibRefCitation>
the duct is similar in size to the vas deferens and extends from the expanded anterior sac (seminal vesicle?) to the sperm pump.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5FAB6FB4FF9AB" blockId="13.[826,1442,1315,1582]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5FAB6FA03FABD" box="[826,1442,1315,1336]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Ejaculatory apodeme, sperm pump, and aedeagus:</emphasis>
The sperm pump and associated ejaculatory apodeme are clearly separated from the base of the external genitalia. The outer wall of the sperm pump is sclerotized and remains intact after being cleared in lactic acid. The pump bears stout opposing muscle sets and clearly functions to pump sperm to the aedeagus. The pump is connected to the aedeagus by a very narrow, clear tube (see 
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FC05F98DFBCBF9A8" author="Cook EF" box="[1002,1130,1560,1582]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" pagination="313 - 319" refId="ref20908" refString="Cook EF. 1981. Scatopsidae. Agriculture Canada Monograph 27: 313 - 319." type="journal article" year="1981">Cook, 1981</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 20.18).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF84B258FCD5F9D3FA97F8F5" blockId="13.[826,1442,1606,1904]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FCD5F9D3FC04F9DE" box="[826,933,1606,1627]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Remarks:</emphasis>
The reproductive tract of 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF84B258FB06F9D3FA00F9D9" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1257,1441,1606,1628]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Scatopse" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="notata">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF84B258FB06F9D3FA00F9D9" box="[1257,1441,1606,1628]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="724">Scatopse notata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FBD7F9F0FB66F9FE" author="Loew H" box="[1080,1223,1637,1659]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" refId="ref22358" refString="Loew H. 1841. Horae Anatomicae, Beitrage zur Genaueren Antomischen Kenntniss der Evertebraten. Abteilung I. Entomotomien. Heine: Posen." type="book" year="1841">Loew (1841)</bibRefCitation>
. Unfortunately, we were not able to trace the configuration of the vasa deferentia in the material available and consequently cannot confirm the observations of 
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF84B258FB36F954FAC8F952" author="Loew H" box="[1241,1385,1729,1751]" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" refId="ref22358" refString="Loew H. 1841. Horae Anatomicae, Beitrage zur Genaueren Antomischen Kenntniss der Evertebraten. Abteilung I. Entomotomien. Heine: Posen." type="book" year="1841">Loew (1841)</bibRefCitation>
. The most striking difference in 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF84B258FB64F94AFAB2F970" box="[1163,1299,1759,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="724" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scatopsidae</taxonomicName>
from other families is the apparent direct connection of the accessory glands to the sperm pump. Further study of the scatopsid male reproductive tract is required in order to confirm and interpret these observations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF87B25BFF48FF56FD0DFEB0" blockId="14.[142,757,195,309]" pageId="14" pageNumber="725">Given the presence of the narrow tube connecting the sperm pump and the aedeagus and the robust sperm pump, an aqueous solution containing spermatozoa is probably pumped through this system.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
